titleproper.value:
Guide to the Downtown Flyers and Invitations Collection
                    <lb/>
                    <date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">ca. 1980-1990</date>
                    <lb/>
                    <num>MSS 119</num>

author.value: Finding aid prepared by Thomas Beachdel,2001. Collection materials added by Robert Feldman in January 2004 and Lisa Darms in July 2008. Johan Kugelberg donation processed by Colin Wells in March 2009.

creation.value:
This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit
                <date>2014-09-16T16:36-0400</date>

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: The collection consists of flyers and invitations relating to downtown galleries, performance spaces, and nightclubs. The bulk of the materials were collected by Mark Swartz, a downtown New York resident.

p.value: Open to researchers. Appointments are necessary for the use of manuscript and archival collections.

Published citations should take the following form:
                <lb/>
                <lb/> Identification of item, date (if known); Downtown Flyer and Invitations; MSS 119; box number; folder number; Fales Library and Special Collections, New York University Libraries.

The bulk of the Downtown Flyers and Invitations Collection consists of material relating to downtown galleries, alternative art spaces, performance spaces, and nightclubs. The collection is particularly strong with regard to material from 
                <corpname>Performing Space 122</corpname>, 
                <corpname>The Alternative Space</corpname> at the West Broadway Gallery, 
                <corpname>The Kitchen</corpname>, and 
                <corpname>La Mama</corpname>. Also, there is a sparse, but nice, collection of nightclub flyers from the 
                <corpname>Limelight</corpname>, the 
                <corpname>Palladium</corpname>, and 
                <corpname>Area</corpname>.
